Recommended Architecture

Add one policy engine in net adapter layer, not multiple fallbacks.
Enforce before command execution in handle_command:
adapter.rs:3201
Enforce inbound delivery before emitting events in poll_udp and poll_tcp:
adapter.rs:3362, adapter.rs:3410
Keep a minimal packet sanity guard only (malformed/bogus), not full nft clone.
Policy Model (Simple and Strong)

Direction: egress, ingress
Owner: app/service owner string
Protocol: tcp, udp, icmp
Remote: CIDR or exact IP
Port rules:
Allow OpenTcpListen only for approved ports
Allow outbound only to approved destinations/ports
Action: allow or deny, with optional log sampling
Default Policy I’d Start With

Default deny ingress listeners, except explicit allow list:
net shell 4245 only if enabled
sntp 123 if needed
ws-time test port only in dev mode
Default allow outbound for known service owners, but with scoped ports:
dns: 53
ntp/sntp client: 123
https/tls: 443
smtp/pop3/irc/ws only if feature/service active
Deny unknown owner listen attempts by default.
What Not To Build Yet

No full conntrack/NAT/state machine like nftables.
No rule language parser or huge DSL now.
No duplicate fallback paths that obscure behavior.
That keeps code smaller and understandable, aligned with your request to avoid dead or confusing fallback code.

When You Should Add Lower-Level Firewalling
Add deeper L3/L4 filtering only if one of these becomes true:

You run untrusted workloads sharing kernel networking.
You expose many inbound services.
You need anti-scan/DoS controls at raw packet level.
You need NAT/bridge/router behavior.
